[src:buck2-build/buck-software] Buck requires the explicit declaration of dependencies.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] Because all dependencies are explicit and Buck has a directed acyclic graph of all source files and build targets, Buck can perform incremental recompilation, only rebuilding targets downstream of files that have changed.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] Buck computes a key for each target that is a hash of the contents of the files it depends on.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] It stores a mapping from that key to the build target in a build cache.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] One of the key features was the ability to share build results between multiple developers and continuous integration (CI), as Buck1 supports a HTTP Cache API.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] In 2023, Buck2 was released, claiming that builds are 2x as fast as compared to Buck1.
[src:buck2-build/buck-software] One of the largest changes from Buck1 is that the core is written in Rust instead of Java, and rules are written outside the core in Starlark (the language created for the Bazel build system).
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] If you've got nothing to do, Buck2 is significantly faster.
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] If you've got lots to do, Buck2 will start doing it faster and be much closer to the critical path.
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] These restrictions apply to both the user-written `BUCK` files and the language rules.
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] Buck2 gives the right result more reliably.
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] All rules are written in Starlark, with nothing in the core of Buck2 knowing anything about languages.
[src:buck2-build/buck2-build] That means that Buck2 users can define their own rules as first-class citizens.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:buck2-build/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:buck2-build/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:buck2-build/page] Welcome to Buck2, a large scale, fast, reliable, and extensible build tool developed and used by Meta.
[src:buck2-build/page] Buck2 supports a variety of languages on many platforms.
[src:buck2-build/page] Starlark, which is a deterministic, immutable dialect of Python, is used to extend the Buck2 build system, enabling Buck2 to be language-agnostic.
[src:buck2-build/page] With Starlark, users can define their own custom rules.
[src:buck2-build/page] Buck2 multi-language support includes C++, Python, Java, Kotlin, Go, Rust, Erlang, OCaml, and more.
[src:buck2-build/page] The following sub-sections contain a list of links to key points in the Buck2 Documentation website that explain the advantages of using Buck2 for you and your team.
[src:buck2-build/page] Feel free to send a PR adding your project.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] A **software build** is the process of converting source code files into standalone software artifact(s) that can be run on a computer, or the result of doing so.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] In include functions such as version control, code quality analysis, compilation, and linking.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] In software production, builds optimize software for performance and distribution, packaging into formats such as '.*exe'; '.deb'; '.apk'*.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The build process often employs specialized tools such as CMake, Make, or Gradle, and integrates with automation systems including Jenkins or GitHub Actions.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Despite advancements, challenges such as dependency conflicts, platform compatibility, and long compile times, remain problems.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] In software development, building software is an end-to-end process that involves many distinct functions.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Some of these functions are described below.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The version control function carries out activities such as workspace creation and updating, baselining and reporting.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] It creates an environment for the build process to run in and captures metadata about the inputs and output of the build process to ensure repeatability and reliability.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Tools such as Git, AccuRev or StarTeam help with these tasks by offering tools to tag specific points in history as being important, and more.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Also known as static program analysis/static code analysis this function is responsible for checking that developers have adhered to the seven axes of code quality: comments, unit tests, duplication, complexity, coding rules, potential bugs and architecture & design.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Ensuring a project has high-quality code results in fewer bugs and influences nonfunctional requirements such as maintainability, extensibility and readability; which have a direct impact on the ROI for a business.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] This is only a small feature of managing the build process.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The compilation function turns source files into directly executable or intermediate objects.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Not every project will require this function.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] While for simple programs the process consists of a single file being compiled, for complex software the source code may consist of many files and may be combined in different ways to produce many different versions.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] A linker or link editor is a computer program that combines intermediate software build files such as object and library files into a single executable file such as a program or library.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] A linker is often part of a toolchain that includes a compiler and/or assembler that generates intermediate files that the linker processes.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The linker may be integrated with other toolchain tools such that the user does not interact with the linker directly.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] A simpler version that writes its output directly to memory is called the *loader*, though loading is typically considered a separate process.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The process of building a computer program is usually managed by a build tool, a program that coordinates and controls other programs.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Examples of such a program are make, Gradle, Ant, Maven, Rake, SCons and Phing.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] The build utility typically needs to compile the various files, in the correct order.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] If the source code in a particular file has not changed then it may not need to be recompiled ("may not" rather than "need not" because it may itself depend on other files that have changed).
[src:buck2-build/software-build] Sophisticated build utilities and linkers attempt to refrain from recompiling code that does not need it, to shorten the time required to complete the build.
[src:buck2-build/software-build] A more complex process may involve other programs producing code or data as part of the build process and software.
